f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_football" title=3D"Gaelic footbal=
l">Gaelic football</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hurling=
" title=3D"Hurling">hurling</a> is a little over a hectare in size.</figcap=
tion></figure>
<p>In 1795, when the metric system was introduced, the <i><b>are</b></i> wa=
s defined as 100 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_metre" tit=
le=3D"Square metre">square metres</a>, or one square <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Decametre" title=3D"Decametre">decametre</a>, and the he=
ctare ("<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hecto-" title=3D"Hecto-">h=
ecto-</a>" + "are") was thus 100 <i>ares</i> or <span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=
=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">1</span><span class=3D"sr-on=
ly">/</span><span class=3D"den">100</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span>&nbsp;km<s=
up>2</sup> (<span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"700410000000000=
0000=E2=99=A0"></span>10<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">000</span></span=
> square metres). When the metric system was further rationalised in 1960, =
resulting in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Sys=
tem_of_Units" title=3D"International System of Units">International System =
of Units</a> (<span class=3D"rt-commentedText tooltip tooltip-dotted" title=
=3D"in French: Syst=C3=A8me International d'Unit=C3=A9s">SI</span>), the <i=
>are</i> was not included as a recognised unit. The hectare, however, remai=
ns as a non-SI unit accepted for use with the SI and whose use is "expected=
 to continue indefinitely". Though the dekare/decare <b>daa</b> (<span clas=
s=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7003100000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>=
1000&nbsp;m<sup>2</sup></span>) and <b>are</b> (100&nbsp;m<sup>2</sup>) are=
 not officially "accepted for use", they are still used in some contexts.
</p>
